[Reading through the 3 media reports and short WHO AFRO report, it appears as though there has been isolation of VDPVs from the affected individuals, but genetic studies and confirmation from a reference lab are still pending.

Information on the age, gender, and laboratory results would be greatly appreciated. An important question is whether the isolated polioviruses are genetically similar, or are they different enough to declare these as 2 separate outbreaks?

Another query is the mention of 2 cases: one in Bimbo and the other in Bambari. Unless these were original locations of residence before displacement, this may be the addition of a 2nd case of AFP identified after the AFRO report was issued. Clarification would be greatly appreciated.

Of interest was a media report from MSF (Médecins sans Frontières; Doctors Without Borders) in early May [2019] that mentioned finally being able to access a community in the south east part of the country (having been cut off due to civil unrest for several years) and begin vaccinations in the area (https://www.doctorswithoutborders.org/what-we-do/news-stories/story/msf-reaches-town-cut-violence-central-african-republic). This may reflect an increasing access to communities previously cut off from services where a VDPV may well have been circulating relatively silently for a significant amount of time. It's also important to mention that CAR has a border with the DR Congo, where there have been multiple outbreaks of cVDPV2 in the past 12 months.

A map showing the prefectures of the Central African Republic can be found at https://www.nationsonline.org/oneworld/map/central-african-republic-administrative-map.htm. Bimbo is located in Ombella-M'Poko prefecture, near to Bangui (the capital city). Bambari is located in Ouaka prefecture.

The HealthMap/ProMED map of the Central African Republic can be found at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=6493464,66. - Mod.MPP]
